Sure, here's a JavaScript program that generates and prints out the ASCII character and hexadecimal codes for 0 to 7F:
```javascript
for (let i = 0; i <= 7F; i++) {
  console.log(`ASCII code: ${i}, Hexadecimal code: ${i.toString(16)}`);
}
```
This program uses a for loop to iterate through the numbers from 0 to 7F, and for each number it prints out both the ASCII character and its hexadecimal code using console.log(). The .toString(16) method is used to convert each number to its hexadecimal representation.
When you run this program in a JavaScript environment such as a web browser's developer console, it will output the following:
```
ASCII code: 0, Hexadecimal code: 0
ASCII code: 1, Hexadecimal code: 1
ASCII code: 2, Hexadecimal code: 2
...
ASCII code: 7F, Hexadecimal code: 7F
```
I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any other questions.
